{{for|her daughter|Blanche Ames Ames}} {{refimprove|date=September 2014}} [[Image:Blanche Butler Ames.jpg|thumb|right|Blanche Butler Ames]] '''Blanche Butler Ames''' (March 2, 1847 – December 26, 1939) was the wife of [[Adelbert Ames]], a decorated general of the [[American Civil War]] and [[United States Senate|Senator]] and [[List of Governors of Mississippi|Governor]] of [[Mississippi]] during Reconstruction.
Blanche Butler was born in [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], the second child and only daughter of [[Sarah Hildreth Butler|Sarah Jones]] (née Hildreth) and [[Benjamin Butler (politician)|Benjamin Franklin Butler]], who would also serve as a general in the Civil War. She attended school in Lowell until she was sent to the Academy of the Visitation in [[Washington, D.C.]] at age 13, where she described the sectional tension between northern and southern students on the eve of the Civil War.
Blanche met Adelbert Ames, who had served under her father in the [[Army of the James]], while he was serving as Senator from Mississippi during [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. They married at Saint Anne's Episcopal Church in Lowell, the same church where her parents were wed, on July 21, 1870, and had six children: [[Butler Ames|Butler]], Edith, Sarah, [[Blanche Ames Ames|Blanche]], [[Adelbert Ames, Jr.|Adelbert, Jr.]], and Jessie. When her husband was elected Governor of Mississippi in 1873, Blanche accompanied him, and wrote a series of letters detailing her experiences as a Northern woman living in the South during Reconstruction. After Adelbert resigned under pressure in 1876, the Ames family returned to Lowell to pursue business interests, where they remained for much the rest of their lives.
After her husband's death in 1933, Mrs. Ames compiled a collection of their letters, released by the family as ''Chronicles from the Nineteenth Century: Family Letters of Blanche Butler and Adelbert Ames'' in 1957. She also compiled a detailed account of the Butler Ancestry in 1895.<ref>''[https://archive.org/details/butlerancestryof00ames The Butler ancestry of Gen. Benjamin Franklin Butler in America]''</ref> She died at the Ames winter home in [[Ormond Beach, Florida]], on December 26, 1939, at the age of 92, and is buried beside her husband and their children at the [[Hildreth Cemetery|Hildreth family cemetery]] in Lowell, across from her parents and siblings.
==Additional Information== * [http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss358_main.html Blanche Butler Ames Papers, 1845-1939], [https://www.smith.edu/libraries/special-collections/about/sophia-smith-collection-womens-history Sophia Smith Collection], Smith College.
